id="OBjjwmxQws1lH1Q7bpvP-1178" value="<b>Time series feature tables</b><div style="text-align: left;"><ul><li>Examples of time-dependent features:&nbsp;time series data, event-based data, or time-aggregated data</li><li>When training a model, we must use only feature values up until the time of the observed target value</li><li>Time series feature tables include a timestamp column that ensures that each row in the training dataset represents the latest known feature values as of the row’s timestamp.</li><li>How point-in-time joining works:&nbsp;</li><ul><li>During FeatureLookup initialization, the feature table (with the timestamp column) and the `timestamp_lookup_key` column name from the labelled data (the "DataFrame") are specified. This tells the API that when the labelled data is fed later, look for the latest feature values from the timestamp column prior to the `timestamp_lookup_key` column.</li><li>During `FeatureEngineering.create_training_set()` invocation, it is provided with the DataFrame, and the lookup object above, and execute the logic.&nbsp;Databricks Feature Store retrieves the latest feature values prior to the timestamps specified in the DataFrame’s timestamp_lookup_key column and whose primary keys (excluding timestamp keys) match the values in the DataFrame’s lookup_key columns, or null if no such feature value exists.</li><li>During&nbsp; `FeatureEngineering.score_batch()`invocation, the input data to score must process the necessary ID and timestamp columns&nbsp;specified in the FeatureLookups of the training_set. If the input data has the same feature column (by name) as the feature table, the input data will be used instead of fetching&nbsp; values from the feature table.</li></ul></ul></div>" </mxCell> <mxCell id="OBjjwmxQws1lH1Q7bpvP-2082" value="Note:<div>The deployment approach here is to retrain the model on full dataset in the STG environment and expose the "UAT endpoint" for testing. One way is to send the logged requests from the prod endpoint inference table to this endpoint and compare the 2 sets of predictions. Another way is to get the UAT team to test it. Though these methods can provide the visibility on the model quality performance, they don't really mimic 100% shadow deployment method, which is not natively available in Databricks. Once the UAT result is deemed satisfactory, the PR is approved (likely manually) and the merging to MAIN branch happens. After that, the release branch can be merged with the MAIN branch, and this triggers the PRD workflows to update the current endpoint with the model copied from the STG catalog. Note that Databricks model serving maintains zero-downtime during the endpoint updating to ensure undisrupted serving.</div><div><br></div><div>Another layer of protection can be via A/B testing (native on Databricks) via traffic splitting in the PRD endpoint updating task. This will need additional codes to extract and compare predictions of the 2 models, and the manual traffic adjustment later depending on the comparison results (either increase new model to 100% or reduce it to 0%). Furthermore, A/B testing works on random allocation of traffic, so it can be unsuitable out-of-the-box for some applications where the traffic from the same ID should be served by the same model.</div>" style="shape=document;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;boundedLbl=1;size=0.09523809523809523;fillColor=#fff2cc;strokeColor=#d6b656;spacing=2;spacingLeft=2;spacingRight=2;spacingBottom=2;spacingTop=2;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="1755" y="4047.66" width="370" height="445.18" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <UserObject label="https://<workspace_url>/serving-endpoints/<endpoint>/invocations" id="OBjjwmxQws1lH1Q7bpvP-2083"> <mxCell style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;fillColor=#fff2cc;strokeColor=#d6b656;fontStyle=2" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="3923.83" y="5160" width="200" height="40" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </UserObject> <UserObject label="<catalog>

Unit tests</b></div><div>- Purpose: ensure no breaking changes to the current modules/functions.</div><div>- Performed by the DevOps runner.</div><div>- No interactions with environment or resources.</div><div><br></div><div><b>2. Integration test (adapted from Databricks MLOps docs)</b></div><div>- Purpose: ensure all workflows can be deployed, validated and run without any error (via DABs)</div><div>- Performed by the STG workspace and its resources, triggered by CLI commands defined in the DevOps tool.</div><div><font style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);">- Method 1 - High fidelity but slower to complete</font>&nbsp;<font style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);">(recommended, especially for deploy-model approach from STG to PRD)</font>&nbsp;</div><div><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>+ all workflows from training to endpoint update are deployed, validated and triggered to run in the STG workspace on "full" training data (e.g., all 3 months' worth of data).&nbsp;</div><div><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>+ The end result is an updated endpoint. This endpoint can be tested by another workflow which simulates request traffics and invokes the endpoint over a defined period of time.</div><div><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>+ Once all workflows run without any failure, the code can be merged into the MAIN branch. The endpoint can be further used for UAT.<br><br></div><div><font style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0);">- Method 2 - Faster to complete but low fidelity (may be suitable if deploy-code approach from STG to PRD is used)</font></div><div><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>+ all workflows are deployed, validated and triggered to run in the STG workspace on a subset of training data (e.g., 7 days out of maximum 3 months' worth of data)<br></div><div><span style="white-space: pre;">	</span>+ The cons of this approach are: (1) the trained model in STG is not fit for promotion in PRD, (2) the endpoint is also not fit for UAT as it is only useful to validate the request-response formats, (3) Custom workflow that omits the model comparison with current @champion, and/or with custom time window is needed.&nbsp;<br></div><div><br></div><div><b>CD Tasks, triggered upon PR from MAIN to RELEASE</b></div><div>- Trigger the deployment, validation and running of PRD workflows (in green).</div><div>- The end result is an updated endpoint with the serving entity equipped with the new model.</div><div>- Note that during endpoint update, Databricks will ensure zero-downtime of the current serving entity until the updated one is up and running.</div><div><br></div><div>TO-DO:</div><div>How to "emergency" roll back the endpoint if the updated one fails after deployment?</div>" especially on spark-based functions are executed in the workspace, not the devops runner. These can be deployed as a separate workflow.</div><b><div><b><br></b></div>Integration tests</b><div>- are separate workflows&nbsp;<span style="background-color: transparent; color: light-dark(rgb(0, 0, 0), rgb(255, 255, 255));">in STG</span></div><div>- run after the main workflows/pipelines run</div><div>- verify a few key things such as whether the data pipelines write to the right tables, if the endpoint is actually updated, etc.</div><div>- integration tests take significant effort, thus they are usually developed and expanded for mission critical, long serving ML models.</div><div>- Else, manual checks on the main workflow running can be sufficient for the start.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Emergency roll-back of endpoint</b></div><div>A quick thing to try is to revert the endpoint serving entity version to a previous version. Though this can be done, the revert should work with the release branch reversal, followed by the redeployment of the DAB.</div><div><br></div><div><b>How to authenticate to the endpoint</b></div><div>PAT is not the recommended way to do it in production, only to test. OAuth should be used instead (Steven will send further info)</div><div><br></div><div><b>Approval of PR</b></div><div>A possible sequence of event (without automatic integration tests and PR approval and merging):&nbsp;</div><div>- CI triggers the workflow(s) to run in STG.&nbsp;</div><div>- If the workflow fails, it sends a signal to the CI to fail the PR.&nbsp;</div><div>- If it is successful, it will send the signal to the CI pipeline to notify a manual review step.&nbsp;</div><div>- The authorized person goes into the PRD workspace and verify the workflow and their tasks (among other checks defined by the team practice), followed by approving the PR manually.</div><div>- Upon merging to MAIN, the merging to RELEASE and the subsequent CD pipeline can be triggered manually or automatically.&nbsp;</div><div>- The CD pipeline validate, deploy and run the relevant workflows to the PRD target.</div>" name="Databricks Overview for Data-AI"> <mxGraphModel dx="1251" dy="707" grid="1" gridSize="10" guides="1" tooltips="1" connect="1" arrows="1" fold="1" page="1" pageScale="1" pageWidth="1654" pageHeight="1169" math="0" shadow="0"> <root> <mxCell id="0" /> <mxCell id="1" parent="0" /> <mxCell id="dsZ1znp0AR_fr1_rP5XN-1" value="<div><div>All Databricks resources and assets are accessible by various means: GUI or code-first approaches with REST API and SDKs.&nbsp;</div></div><div>Engine and runtime: enables distributed data processing for both DE and DS workloads, from data processing to model training, with respective Spark APIs, Spark clusters (serverless and managed) and out-of-the-box runtimes. The distributed nature is suitable for enterprises with large data amounts. The use of managed (but customizable) runtimes minimize many common compatibility and reproducibility problems across environments during development, testing and production.</div><div>Code versioning and CICD: Natural integration with Git providers without any need to change the way Python projects are modularized and tested.</div><div>Model Management: Model lifecycle and training experiment management tool with industry-standard MLflow, to put structure and reproducibility to the highly dynamic and iterative model training/testing process.</div><div>AutoML: for initial development, built-in AutoML tool provides great visibility on the potential model development directions by automatically run data profiling and model experiments on your data with GUI.</div><div>Serving of ML models for all throughput-latency combinations</div><blockquote style="margin: 0 0 0 40px; border: none; padding: 0px;"><div>Very low latency, low throughput: Endpoint serving infrastructure, customized and deployed in simple APIs/SDKs, highly integrated with upstream MLflow.</div><div>High latency, high throughput: batch serving with Spark</div><div>Low-medium latency, medium throughput: streaming with Spark</div></blockquote><div>Monitoring of ML model serving (both model performance and input data drifts) with Lakehouse monitoring. This is the trigger for data driven ML model retraining (apart from time-trigger by the orchestration tool below). Other system monitoring like endpoint response time and compute utilization are also available.</div><div><div>Data asset governance tool with Unity Catalog, which applies to data, models and other environment assets and resources.&nbsp;</div></div><blockquote style="margin: 0 0 0 40px; border: none; padding: 0px;"><div><div>This tool is used by all personas in the development cycle from DE to DS and DA, eliminating the need of different security provisions.&nbsp;</div></div><div><div>Hence, instead of jumping through loops (complex security objects and secret management) to grant and access these assets, all personas can be granted access by the same way and access these assets by 1-liner codes.&nbsp; This also enable data discoverability and sharing as the output of DE workloads are visible to downstream developers for immediate usage.&nbsp;</div></div><div><div>This governance tool is highly customizable to handle small to large organization structures and their segregation needs.</div></div><div><div>In addition, its flexibility enables easy configuration of cross-environment access.</div></div></blockquote><div><div>Data lineage is built-in (if the correct APIs are used) so that for example, the model can be traced back to its source feature tables, and in turn their source tables. This applies to tables alone as well.</div><div>Data as Feature store is built-in through delta tables and feature engineering SDKs. This is crucial in ensuring reliable model training and inference.</div><div>Orchestration tools (pipelines, workflows) without external 3rd party tools (like Azure Data Factory, Airflow…), making it convenient to build and automate all workloads by all personas. Now, DS don’t need to rely on DE to build orchestrations for DS workloads. They just need to collaborate and ensure their workloads are in-sync.&nbsp;</div><div>Infrastructure as code with Databricks Asset Bundles. This tool simplifies and ensure quality + reproducibility of the deployment task by encapsulating all components (codes, runtime, env-variables/parameters…) into an object that can deploy and run in any target environment (workspace).</div></div><div><div>A hub for hosted and governed GenAI models and features: some are</div></div><blockquote style="margin: 0 0 0 40px; border: none; padding: 0px;"><div><div>hosted LLMs accessible by codes via API calls,&nbsp;</div></div><div><div>Databricks (AI) Assistant for developers (like Github Copilot but with Databricks “knowledge”),&nbsp;</div></div><div><div>Tools for LLM-Ops,&nbsp;</div></div><div><div>AI/BI Genie for GenAI on top of data (e.g., table QnA) – this is extremely tough to build and maintained with separate tools like UI, web server, backend vector store, hosted LLM, etc.</div></div></blockquote><div><br></div>" ul.li: Examples of time-dependent features: time series data, event-based data, or time-aggregated data
When training a model, we must use only feature values up until the time of the observed target value
Time series feature tables include a timestamp column that ensures that each row in the training dataset represents the latest known feature values as of the row’s timestamp.

During FeatureLookup initialization, the feature table (with the timestamp column) and the `timestamp_lookup_key` column name from the labelled data (the "DataFrame") are specified. This tells the API that when the labelled data is fed later, look for the latest feature values from the timestamp column prior to the `timestamp_lookup_key` column.

During `FeatureEngineering.create_training_set()` invocation, it is provided with the DataFrame, and the lookup object above, and execute the logic. Databricks Feature Store retrieves the latest feature values prior to the timestamps specified in the DataFrame’s timestamp_lookup_key column and whose primary keys (excluding timestamp keys) match the values in the DataFrame’s lookup_key columns, or null if no such feature value exists.

During `FeatureEngineering.score_batch()`invocation, the input data to score must process the necessary ID and timestamp columns specified in the FeatureLookups of the training_set. If the input data has the same feature column (by name) as the feature table, the input data will be used instead of fetching values from the feature table.

Validation - Registration Steps, Given the hyperopt experiment
I. FORMAT AND METADATA VALIDATION
*Assuming the model algorithm is pre-determined, else modify the details.
1. Model Format: Verify that the model is saved in a compatible format. For example: the model is a SKlearn Pipeline class instance, where the last component is an estimator of a LGBM class instance...
2. Signature Validation: Check that the model signature (input and output schema) is present, correctly defined and matches the expected format.
3. Metadata Completeness: Ensure that all necessary metadata (e.g., model version, training data schema, hyperparameters) are logged and complete.
II. PERFORMANCE VALIDATION
1. select best run based on performance on the test set
2. Compare the best run performance on a fixed threshold. If higher than threshold, proceed to next step.
3. Load the current "champion" model from the "prd" catalog and evaluate it on the same test set. If the best run model has a higher performance, proceed to next step.
4. Register the best run model to the current catalog, with alias = "challenger". It is now ready for staging/UAT inference before the decision to promote it to "champion".
III. COMPLIANCE VALIDATION IF ANY

li.font: Reset feature and raw target tables
Initialize the tables with 3 months of data
Train a baseline pipeline model and register it to the target UC with @champion alias.
Create prediction-feedback table, set up monitoring.
Set moving window limit and frequency - 1 Apr to 31 Dec 2017, 1min = 1 day
Update feature tables from biz tables: every 1 minute, 1 day is added to the ending timestamp of the feature engineering refresh code.

span.font: Logic: get the last date in the feature tables, add 1 day, use this to engineer more feature rows from the biz tables and add to the feature tables by the sequence below.

li.font: `olist_orders_features` table: use timestamp from orders table.
Mimic user requests: every 1 min, 1 day worth of requests are sent to the endpoint. The requests will use the features in step 2.
Mimic feedback loop: every 1 min, 1 day worth of reviews from the review table (based on review timestamp) will be joined with the prediction payload table to produce the prediction-feedback table.

div.div:
1. why feature engineering ("raw" units) is outside of model preprocessing:
1. reusable
2. bounded and scaled
3. user request limit
4. monitor drift in data stats
5. depends on model algo2. Why need a separate pipeline for ground truths?
This is to have flexibility and adapt to different business requirements.
What is considered "truth" depends on the business definition and requirements, which can in turn change with time.
For example, for a subscription business, the definition of "churn" may be as simple as "anyone who is no longer a subscriber last month" and can be easily derived from the existing customer table. For an e-commerce business, it can be "anyone without purchases in the last 3 months" at one point, and "anyone without purchases in the last 1 month" later.
Thus, building a separate pipeline for ground truth can adapt to this nature.
In addition, the ground truth table can be kept lean if handled separately.

div.div:
Note:
The deployment approach here is to retrain the model on full dataset in the STG environment and expose the "UAT endpoint" for testing. One way is to send the logged requests from the prod endpoint inference table to this endpoint and compare the 2 sets of predictions. Another way is to get the UAT team to test it. Though these methods can provide the visibility on the model quality performance, they don't really mimic 100% shadow deployment method, which is not natively available in Databricks. Once the UAT result is deemed satisfactory, the PR is approved (likely manually) and the merging to MAIN branch happens. After that, the release branch can be merged with the MAIN branch, and this triggers the PRD workflows to update the current endpoint with the model copied from the STG catalog. Note that Databricks model serving maintains zero-downtime during the endpoint updating to ensure undisrupted serving.
Another layer of protection can be via A/B testing (native on Databricks) via traffic splitting in the PRD endpoint updating task. This will need additional codes to extract and compare predictions of the 2 models, and the manual traffic adjustment later depending on the comparison results (either increase new model to 100% or reduce it to 0%). Furthermore, A/B testing works on random allocation of traffic, so it can be unsuitable out-of-the-box for some applications where the traffic from the same ID should be served by the same model.

div.b: CI Tasks, triggered upon PR from DEV to MAIN
div.div: - Purpose: ensure no breaking changes to the current modules/functions.
- No interactions with environment or resources.

div.b: 2. Integration test (adapted from Databricks MLOps docs)

div.div: - Purpose: ensure all workflows can be deployed, validated and run without any error (via DABs)
- Performed by the STG workspace and its resources, triggered by CLI commands defined in the DevOps tool.

div.font: - Method 1 - High fidelity but slower to complete
(recommended, especially for deploy-model approach from STG to PRD)

div.div: + all workflows from training to endpoint update are deployed, validated and triggered to run in the STG workspace on "full" training data (e.g., all 3 months' worth of data).
+ The end result is an updated endpoint. This endpoint can be tested by another workflow which simulates request traffics and invokes the endpoint over a defined period of time.
+ Once all workflows run without any failure, the code can be merged into the MAIN branch. The endpoint can be further used for UAT.

div.font: - Method 2 - Faster to complete but low fidelity (may be suitable if deploy-code approach from STG to PRD is used)

div.div: + all workflows are deployed, validated and triggered to run in the STG workspace on a subset of training data (e.g., 7 days out of maximum 3 months' worth of data)

+ The cons of this approach are: (1) the trained model in STG is not fit for promotion in PRD, (2) the endpoint is also not fit for UAT as it is only useful to validate the request-response formats, (3) Custom workflow that omits the model comparison with current @champion, and/or with custom time window is needed.

div.b: CD Tasks, triggered upon PR from MAIN to RELEASE

div.div: - Trigger the deployment, validation and running of PRD workflows (in green).
- The end result is an updated endpoint with the serving entity equipped with the new model.
- Note that during endpoint update, Databricks will ensure zero-downtime of the current serving entity until the updated one is up and running.

div.div: In Databricks, unit tests especially on spark-based functions are executed in the workspace, not the devops runner. These can be deployed as a separate workflow.
- run after the main workflows/pipelines run
- verify a few key things such as whether the data pipelines write to the right tables, if the endpoint is actually updated, etc.
- integration tests take significant effort, thus they are usually developed and expanded for mission critical, long serving ML models.
- Else, manual checks on the main workflow running can be sufficient for the start.

A quick thing to try is to revert the endpoint serving entity version to a previous version. Though this can be done, the revert should work with the release branch reversal, followed by the redeployment of the DAB.

div.b: How to authenticate to the endpoint

div.div: PAT is not the recommended way to do it in production, only to test. OAuth should be used instead (Steven will send further info)
A possible sequence of event (without automatic integration tests and PR approval and merging):
- CI triggers the workflow(s) to run in STG.
- If the workflow fails, it sends a signal to the CI to fail the PR.
- If it is successful, it will send the signal to the CI pipeline to notify a manual review step.
- The authorized person goes into the PRD workspace and verify the workflow and their tasks (among other checks defined by the team practice), followed by approving the PR manually.
- Upon merging to MAIN, the merging to RELEASE and the subsequent CD pipeline can be triggered manually or automatically.
- The CD pipeline validate, deploy and run the relevant workflows to the PRD target.

# This is a Databricks asset bundle definition for classic_serverless_benchmarking.
# See https://docs.databricks.com/dev-tools/bundles/index.html for documentation.
bundle:
  name: PSA_DAB_Training
  uuid: c6750bee-35be-4e47-9714-d3ff2bcc938d

include:
  - resources/*.yml

###################################
# Variables name  
# - Custom variables for the bundle
###################################
variables:
# Setting the variables for my_user_name, catalog_name, schema_name
  my_user_name:
    description: Add your user name
    default: ${workspace.current_user.short_name}

  catalog_name:
    description: Consider all 3 environments write the same catalog, just different schemas.
    default: steventan
   
  schema_dev:
    description: Development schema for the project. Append _dev to the user name.
    default: ${var.my_user_name}_dev

  schema_staging:
    description: Staging schema for the project. Append _staging to the user name.
    default: ${var.my_user_name}_staging

  schema_prod:
    description: Prod schema for the project. Append _prod to the user name.
    default: ${var.my_user_name}_prod

# The target_catalog and raw_data_path variables will be used when deploying to our development and production environments. These will populate the job parameters' values based on the environment.
  target_schema:
    description: Target schema to use for deployment - default is 'dev'.
    default: ${var.schema_dev}

targets:
  dev:
    # The default target uses 'mode: development' to create a development copy.
    # - Deployed resources get prefixed with '[dev my_user_name]'
    # - Any job schedules and triggers are paused by default.
    # See also https://docs.databricks.com/dev-tools/bundles/deployment-modes.html.
    mode: development
    default: true
    workspace:
      host: https://adb-984752964297111.11.azuredatabricks.net

  stage:
    mode: production
    workspace:
      host: https://adb-984752964297111.11.azuredatabricks.net
      # We explicitly deploy to /Workspace/Users/steven.tan@databricks.com to make sure we only have a single copy.
      root_path: /Workspace/Users/${workspace.current_user.userName}/.bundle/${bundle.name}/${bundle.target}
    ## Change variable values when in the staging environment to use the staging schema
    variables:
        target_schema: ${var.schema_staging}

  prod:
    mode: production
    workspace:
      host: https://adb-984752964297111.11.azuredatabricks.net
      # We explicitly deploy to /Workspace/Users/steven.tan@databricks.com to make sure we only have a single copy.
      root_path: /Workspace/Users/${workspace.current_user.userName}/.bundle/${bundle.name}/${bundle.target}
    run_as:
      service_principal_name: '401342bb-545b-40ab-a0b0-2b05a82fe7ec'

    ## Change variable values when in the production environment to use the production schema
    variables:
        target_schema: ${var.schema_prod}
